Rebel in Time was a definite attempt between myself and the publisher. I had the idea. I saw the idea as being something that a non-science fiction reader would buy. Science fiction sells 20% of all fiction in the United States in paperback, which is not bad. But being a writer, I see 80% more I could sell. And a publisher like to sell more, too. So we talked about the novel. I said it's pure science fiction, but it starts out as a mystery novel. And it's a good quarter of the way into it before the science fiction element is brought in. And it's a science fiction element that the reader will accept, any general reader. And by that time, he's trapped. And I think, if you think you can sell as a mainstream novel, let's try it. And I turned the manuscript in England, America, and I said, yes, we're going to try and sell this to everybody. And 10, 20 years ago, I couldn't have done that because I had no big name, and the readers would not have bought it. Now, I have enough readers around. They'll see it, my name on it. They'll look at it, open it, maybe buy it. The science fiction readers. So I don't think we'll lose one science fiction reader by packaging it that way. We might pick up a lot of other readers, which make me happy, my publisher happy, my wife happy, my children, my bank manager, you know, all the things we want to make happy. Okay. We've talked a bit about your novels, but we haven't mentioned short stories. And you've written one or two of those. How do you attack a short story as opposed to a novel? How do they occur to you? In science fiction, unlike a lot of other fiction, there are people who write both short stories and novels. Some of them can, but a lot of them can. And very simply, it is least residual. A short story is a one-idea story. If a single gimmick or device or turn of plot, you write that to length and stop it at two or three or four or five thousand words. If it's complicated, it goes to 10,000 novelettes. As opposed to a novel, which is a complex thought that requires modifications, more than one idea, ramifications, and then it goes to novel length. And many times I first started writing, I had some short story ideas. And they're very good to do. They go in the magazines, they go in anthologies, read, recognize your name. And deliberately, between novels, we do a half dozen short stories. Unhappily, after a number of years of writing, you find publishers want to give you more money for novels. And they really do. The word rate per word in a novel is about 10 times a short story. And I find myself tending to cook one novel onto the end of the other. I haven't written a short story in three or four or five years, which I think is a shame because I have four collections of short stories out, all selling quite nicely, and they've anthologized in about 22 languages. But in the history of time, I found a time in life I wanted to anthologize, and I did. A time in life I wanted to write short stories, I did. Now I'm tending to write longer and longer books, like Rebel in Time, the current book, which will be about a quarter of a million words at least, perhaps longer. Not because I want to write a long book, because a very complex idea requires that amount of time to work out. And there again, it's right as lives go in the waves like the ocean. You surge up the beach, a lot of dead things in it, and go away out to the ocean again, the clear depths, and you produce different things at different times. If you could write anything you want, not worrying about economic exigencies, would you stick to short stories? Would they mean that much to you? I'm happy to say that for the last 20-odd years, I've never written a thing I didn't want to write. I've turned down assignments I didn't enjoy, and I've written just exactly the books and short stories I wanted to write. It's a nice position to be in, too. I read the books that you've signed so far, the collections. I think I have all the collections, so I read all those collected short stories plus some insinorologies, and Rescue Operation Far and Away was my favorite. Really? That's unusual here. Yes, Rescue Operation. There again, I see one idea. That Rescue Operation came out. Everything in there I know except the alien. In Yugoslavia, the most broken-down country in Western Europe, they have peasants there, which are much more broken-down than German peasants. They have deeply religious, simple-mindedly stupid people-burning peasants within 10 miles of a nuclear reactor. The perfect analog of our world. Instead of northern civilized countries, southern poor, uncivilized countries all in one country, and having been in the middle of this and having had a number of desperately awful things happen to me and my family down there. The children got scarlet fever, had had injections with blunt needles, had to carry them screaming, you know, sort of thing. And I was living in that desperate, awful world, and there again, the background was there. And then the thought, whew, instead of arriving in Central Park in front of the White House, what if the alien from space arrived there? Voila, you know, complete. Just a matter of writing it. I was also very moved by the one, I'm terrible in the names and titles, the one where you said you got the idea when you were in Europe and wherever you were you heard that Martin Luther King had been shot and somebody said he was just in the middle. That's right. Not me, not Amos Cabot. No, that's not the level thing. I'll come again. That's not a short story. Yeah, Mute Milton. Mute Milton. Yeah. Living in Scandinavia, been out of the States two or three or four years and the Danes are absolutely colorblind that in fact in those days really certain kind of girls only date black men. Other girls used to look down upon them. There were about four black men in the whole country, you know. And you know, it's very easy to be pro-race, anti-racist if you're in a country with no race problems. But living there, children growing up there, and Martin Luther King was shot and a newspaper called me and asked me what my opinion on it, you know, and we're all horrified. And then I picked a copy of Newsweek up and they had some great big belly Alabama. I photographed him with a shotgun in one hand, a nose picker in the other, and his belly hangover is his belt, you know, saying, well, just one more nigger to me. And I just, my white heat engulfed my mind. One of Americans, he got a Nobel Prize earlier than that. You know, one of Americans, well, I was very proud when he came over there. I was in Scandinavia, he's an American getting a prize for doing something really good in the world, being honored for it. And I saw red and the idea came to me, you know, for the story and just, again, to put into a story that rage I had, that strong feeling. And so my background there is in mechanics. I can know there's mechanics. And I did major in biology in school before I went in. And I keep my reading up. That's all. I mean, a science fiction writer shouldn't, you know, be a jackdaw of science. You should know enough about any science to read an article on it and know what they're talking about, what I do. The nice part is that among science fiction readers there's so many closet readers who have other jobs. Every engineer in the world in every school used to be a science fiction fan. Professors of this biology, linguistics. And they love this stuff. And I have a problem. I just grabbed some professor. A doctor teaching physics said, tell me about that. They'll sit down because you know yourself. Any engineer, all he wants to do is talk about a speciality over and over and over again. I love to hear about it. And I pin these guys down. I know enough about the basics of mechanics and biology and nuclear theory to understand what they're talking about. And for a while, I'm an authority on it. I did Skyfall. I had a science fiction fan in England who was an upper atmosphere specialist. I was about three in the world at the time. A typical British program sending British packages up in American rockets from Norway, you know, into the upper atmosphere. And for one while there, I had charts. I understood all about orbital mechanics. I know everything about it for one glorious month or two. I did that chapter. It's all gone now. And again, to answer the question, I know the areas I don't know and I know enough to ask somebody and I know enough to get it right and have them check it out. You really should do your sums in science fiction. Get your facts right and then work around them. Known facts should be right and make up your own facts afterwards. Skyfall was almost prophetic, wasn't it? Not almost. Skyfall was prophetic. Yeah, now twice. Skyfall was prophetic in the sense that there again, from the literature, I discovered that the Russians and the Americans were lying to the world. These great big boosters did not burn upon re-entry. They just flashed down the ocean and what they were doing was relying upon the law of averages. Three quarters of the world is water, right? 98% of the land is desert or mountain, right? So the chances are you're never going to drop it on somebody. Oh yeah, I said. This friend in the rocket program showed me Radio Sun rocket they sent up with, you know, that instrumentation in the nose was supposed to do important things in the upper atmosphere and it had failed. It went up 150 miles, turned over under full blast and blasted down at full speed into the ground. Dusted off, it's still working. You know, so no, they don't burn up in the atmosphere and I said, one of these days they're going to drop one of these things in the wrong place and they're big and they weigh tons and tons and tons and we're being lied to. And so then again, that's a plot and I worked on a plot where you're dropping on something big and what do you know, a little bit later and the interesting part was, doubly prophetic in that at this point we didn't know the upper atmosphere very much and Professor Webb was telling me that he said, gee, you know, we just discovered the upper atmosphere is so tenuous that when a photon storm, the solar flare large one hits the upper atmosphere it can move up a matter of 50, 80 miles in a matter of minutes because it's so, as the heat enters these molecules they expand, up it goes and, wow, I said, plot device, I needed a way of stopping my orbiting ship to get it down in one spot. Solar storm, it goes around the back of the earth comes out like hitting a wall and falls. Guess why Skylab came down? They put Skylab in an orbit they did not know this happened, it came down for just that reason and I plucked out of this guy's mind. That's fun to do, let me tell you. I'll ask you two more questions then. One of them, it just occurred to me, what, what, what's it like to raise a family, marry, raise a family, be a science fiction writer. What, what does your wife and family have to put up with? Well, you really should ask my wife, you really should ask my wife that. It's, it's never boring. Yeah, I'll be honest. All right? That's all I'm trying to say. Writers are a pretty dim lot to begin with. They, and I know a lot of them. They're, they're people eaters, they're cantankerous. What they do, they really, uh, want her right and do nothing else. And women don't really like them. They, they, they change a lot of wives. Not because the women can't put up this nonsense. And the ones that stay married because they marry a woman who is nice enough or smart enough or commodious enough to entertain their style of life to permit them to do this sort of thing and put up all their nonsense. I'm happy to say my dear wife doesn't mind moving to Mexico with a one-year-old baby and living in a small town with fleas and giving the kid malaria. She doesn't mind going to Denmark or England or Italy. Um, and it, um, that's just the way it works. The writing's not going to change. Uh, it's really up to the wife to put up with the nonsense and the kids, kids grow up in any conditions. Kids think whatever they have is normal. So that, they're not a problem at all as long as you think about them. I think it took a joke for a lot of good. It's like, automatically learned a lot of language. They thought it was normal to speak more than normal and go to different schools. And then they had to get back to the States because they knew people who were American and they lived it and knew what it meant. So we tried it out. And one decided to remain European and the other decided to remain American and they bought that. I guess I should ask why the movement around, if that's a fair question, I don't know. What is it that Nichols' encyclopedia says you're... Peripatetic? Yes, that's the word. Good word. I want to edit it. I looked it up. Yeah, you looked it up. Yeah. I had to look it up. Yeah, one editor, um, we should know how you increase your vocabulary, you know, that's why I love to read Graham Greene. And Anthony Burgess, you look up words. Kingsley Amis. Kingsley Amis, one book that said, uh, this is back in the 50s and it must have been a Studebaker. He said, out in the street in New York, I saw a rather amphibionic car. Amphibionic car? What the hell is that? It means a creature with a face on both ends. There are certain worms that look like a face on both ends. Amphib, physiognomy, bionium. So great. Now, that's how you increase your vocabulary. But, uh, yeah, parapateticism, some are born parapatetic, some attain parapateticism, some have it thrust upon them. Not bad, you can't do it every day of the week. I think, um, I fall into all three categories. I couldn't work in New York. I'd been in Mexico a few times, a station in the border in the war. I liked it very, very much. I liked the whole way of life. And I went to Mexico and we lived there for a year and then couldn't, it was just too boring and too simple and nothing much going on with the family. And then I wanted to go to England. And once you start moving, you find it's much easier to keep going. And the answer basically is, like when you ask someone, someone asks me, why I raise a beard. I ask them, why they shave theirs off? And is it, why are you living in Texas? And if you're, you're always in Texas, but why aren't you living in England? when I, I never seen a place that I didn't want to visit. And I find it's utterly fascinating to learn about cultures. I think, I told, um, a number of times that different science fiction writers, if you're writing about other cultures, shouldn't you see a little bit more than your own culture? Shouldn't you get around? And, um, I find it utterly fascinating to go into a new culture, meet a new kind of life, to speak a new language, and see how people work. And I think it must be reflected in my work. Well, you also said, honey, you couldn't write about the future, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what, what are you after, and how do you want to be remembered? I'm after, like John Campbell, you say, staying alive forever. No, no, uh, how do you want to be remembered? I don't want to be remembered, I want to be here. That's a very simple answer. oh, writing is a very satisfying craft. When you do it, you're satisfied. What you're doing, if you're doing it well. But then, uh, it's not like, I don't really believe that real writers write in closets for them, their own pleasure. Then, you're, it's a communication. It's like talking in sex. You're, it's interrelationship going all the time. Then after having done to best your ability something, you want to publish it and see if anybody knows what the hell you said. And that's interesting. See if you succeeded in what you were trying to do. See, as an artist, I was always doing artwork and getting it out there. So I'm used to having a feedback public. And, uh, then again, if you would all feel about the state of the world, the writer is a very privileged state, the science fiction writer, he can give lectures and he can tell people what to do and he can warn them, you know, in a very hectoring tone of voice. And, uh, if you can do all those things, it's a satisfactory way of getting from A to B, you know, a lot more satisfactory than working at McDonald's. That's so much. How can we top that?
